observations.recommendation:
We recommended that management:
Expedite the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances in compliance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, and allocate necessary funds for its implementation;
Submit a formal request to the COA Regional Office X Training Unit for the conduct of training on PPE Management and One-Time Cleansing of PPE; or
Attend relevant trainings offered by accredited professional organizations, such as the PICPA and GACPA, if available; and
Consider consulting government personnel from other LGUs or national agencies that have successfully conducted the One-Time Cleansing to gather insights and strategies for developing an effective Physical Inventory Plan;
Direct the OMA and GSO-Designate to conduct regular reconciliation between physical asset counts and accounting records, and augment manpower in both offices to immediately complete the reconciliation and tracing of discrepancies;
Mobilize the Inventory Committee and require them to conduct a physical count of PPE. Assign additional committee members or support staff to assist in the activity, as necessary and appropriate;
Instruct the GSO-Designate to exclude from the RPCPPE all items with acquisition costs below the capitalization threshold, and to indicate key identifying information – such as the plate numbers, serial numbers, and property numbers – for each PPE item included, to ensure accurate and efficient tracking;
Require the GSO-designate to indicate the condition of PPE (e.g., serviceable, unserviceable, idle) in the RPCPPE to provide a more accurate assessment of the usability and value of government assets, in compliance with inventory reporting standards; and
Direct the GSO-Designate and the OMA to diligently maintain and regularly update the PPE Inventory Cards and PPE Ledger Cards, respectively, ensuring that all relevant information is accurately recorded to facilitate effective monitoring, accountability, and compliance.

We recommended that management:
Submit to the COA Auditor, for validation purposes, the SB Resolution authorizing the Municipal Mayor to sign the Deed of Donation for the ramp pump at Mandaing, together with the corresponding Deed of Donation duly received by the PGB;
Make reporesentations and consistently follow up with the PGB for the execution of the Deeds of Donation for the unrecorded PPEs;
Require the Municipal Accountant, upon receipt of the Deeds, to immediately record the costs of the assets, including appropriate adjustments to the carrying value by accounting for depreciation costs for prior years from the date of completion of the assets;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to include disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements regarding the unrecorded PPE; and
Ensure thereafter that Deeds of Donation from source agencies are promptly requested and secured once PPE projects for the LGU are completed and ready for their intended use, if such execution is required under existing Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) to effect the transfer of ownership.

We recommended that management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Exhaust all available records and supporting documents to identify and validate the affected PPE items, prepare appropriate working papers, and submit them to COA for verification;
Provide adequate disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements regarding the depreciation expense, specifically highlighting the absence of itemized breakdowns for certain PPE items;
Expedite the conduct of the one-time cleansing of PPE, in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006, to facilitate the proper itemization, valuation, and updating of the depreciable cost and useful life of assets, and reflect necessary adjustments in the books;
Ensure that all future depreciation lapsing schedules include itemized breakdowns of PPE, with complete details such as acquisition date, JEV reference, description, cost, and applicable depreciation rates; and
Establish and maintain a central repository or digital system for PPE documentation (e.g., scanned PARs, JEVs, acquisition papers) to support future audits and improve data reliability.

We recommended to the management to:
Submit a justification for the conduct of physical count of inventory equivalent to 3.43% only of the PPE balances;
Require the Inventory Committee to complete the physical count of PPEs, and;
Conduct One-Time cleansing of PPEs.

We recommended to the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare journal entry vouchers for the proper classification of the above-cited long-outstanding balances which shall then form part of the LGU’s surplus, and may be used as other source of funds for a supplemental budget, and;
Prepare journal entry vouchers for the proper classification of the long-outstanding liabilities to NGAs or other organization, prepare liquidation reports and return excess/unused funds, if any.

Management should do the following:
1.	Require the Inventory Committee to immediately conduct physical count of inventories (especially the construction materials), and;
2. 	Prospectively, require the Municipal Accountant to record every issuance of construction materials as part of the Construction in Progress, as prescribed.

We recommended to the management the following:
The MEO to regularly furnish and update the OMA of the status of projects being implemented by the LGU;
The OMA and MEO to regularly reconcile their records to reflect a consistent and accurate information regarding the status of projects;
The MEO to submit certificates of completion for projects already completed which were still reported as CIP in the accounting books, and;
The OMA to create an adjusting entry to reclassify the said projects to their appropriate asset accounts.

We recommended to the management to:
Submit a justification for the conduct of physical count of inventory equivalent to 3.43% only of the PPE balances;
Require the Inventory Committee to complete the physical count of PPEs, and;
Conduct One-Time cleansing of PPEs.

We recommended to the Municipal Accountant to:
Prepare journal entry vouchers for the proper classification of the above-cited long-outstanding balances which shall then form part of the LGU’s surplus, and may be used as other source of funds for a supplemental budget, and;
Prepare journal entry vouchers for the proper classification of the long-outstanding liabilities to NGAs or other organization, prepare liquidation reports and return excess/unused funds, if any.

Management should do the following:
1.	 Require the immediate preparation of RIS and SSMI for the already consumed/ issued inventories (especially the construction materials) for its proper accounting;
2.	Require the Inventory Committee to immediately conduct physical count of inventories (especially the construction materials), and;
3.	 Prospectively, require the Municipal Accountant to record every issuance of construction materials as part of the Construction in Progress, as prescribed.

Management to:
1.	Ensure that the guidelines for official local travels of government personnel as prescribed in COA Circular No. 96-004 are strictly followed, and;
2.	Submit certificated of appearance and official receipts of the above-mentioned transactions with incomplete supporting documents otherwise, shall be suspended in audit.

Management to:
1.	Require the submission of duly verified/accepted accomplishment reports or the approved daily time records (DTRs) in every claim of honorarium of the workers and volunteers, and;
2.	Ensure that disbursements are recorded in the proper accounts as prescribed by the revised LGU Chart of Accounts.

We recommended that the management will coordinate with Landbank of the Philippines for the immediate reconciliation of the noted variance on the recorded balance of the Loans Payable account. Reconciling items should be adjusted immediately to bring both records into agreement; 

That reconciliation shall be conducted at least once a year; and

That the Accounting Office shall maintain separate subsidiary ledgers for each loan account.

We recommended to the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board (MSWMB) to:

Reinforce involvement and participation of barangay through massive information dissemination of the municipality’s solid waste management programs;

Support the establishment of fully functional MRF for each barangay or cluster of barangays. In the meantime, for barangays without MRF, provide appropriate trash bins with proper labels on assigned collection areas;

Continue strict monitoring of areas where: (a) indiscriminate dumping of waste is rampant, if any; and (b) burning of wastes was being practiced;

Continue to enforce all regulations to the extent of imposing penalties for non-compliance.

Hasten the construction of sanitary landfill.

Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly adhere to the provisions of Section 114 and 121 of the NGAS Manual.

